---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import { SOCIALS } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title="About" description="A bit about Drew — what I build, what I break, and what I'm currently obsessing over." />
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main class="main">
			<article class="about">
				<header class="about-header">
					<h1>About</h1>
				</header>

				<div class="about-content">
					<p>
						Hi, I'm Drew. I write code across the stack but spend most of my
						free time near the bottom of it — emulators, databases, backends,
						and the homelab humming away in the next room.
					</p>

					<p>
						Right now I'm building a <strong>CHIP-8 emulator in Rust</strong>,
						which is my excuse to keep poking at low-level systems and the kind
						of bugs that don't show up in a stack trace. Before that I built
						<strong>godbms</strong>, a database from scratch in Go, and
						<strong>beaver</strong>, a Go service for backing the database up. I
						like understanding things by rebuilding them.
					</p>

					<p>
						On the distributed-systems side I built a
						<strong>Twitter-style microservice in Python</strong> to dig into
						the fanout-on-write vs fanout-on-read tradeoff — there's a writeup
						on that in the posts. I also wrote
						<strong>cloudarr</strong>, a Go tool that backs my homelab media off
						to cloud storage, and a handful of smaller things like
						<strong>browser-grep</strong>, a TypeScript extension for searching
						across open tabs.
					</p>

					<!-- <p>
						The rest of my time goes to the homelab — Proxmox, LXC containers,
						a Minecraft-on-demand setup, and the occasional self-inflicted
						outage when I flip a container from unprivileged to privileged
						without thinking it through. Those make for good posts.
					</p> -->

					<p>
						This blog is where I write about the things I'm building and
						breaking. Expect notes on Rust, Go, databases, distributed systems,
						homelab tinkering, and a bit of security. If any of that sounds
						interesting, the posts page is probably a better starting point
						than this one.
					</p>
				</div>

				<footer class="about-footer social-icons">
					{SOCIALS.map((s) => (
						<a
							href={s.url}
							target={s.url.startsWith('http') ? '_blank' : undefined}
							rel={s.url.startsWith('http') ? 'noopener noreferrer' : undefined}
							aria-label={s.label}
						>
							{s.label}
						</a>
					))}
				</footer>
			</article>
		</main>
		<Footer />

		<style>
			.main {
				max-width: calc(var(--main-width) + var(--gap) * 2);
				margin: auto;
				padding: var(--gap);
			}
			.about-header {
				margin: 24px auto 24px;
			}
			.about-header h1 {
				margin: 0;
				font-size: 40px;
				font-weight: 700;
				line-height: 1.2;
				color: var(--primary);
			}
			.about-content p {
				font-size: 16px;
				line-height: 1.7;
				color: var(--primary);
				margin: 0 0 18px;
			}
			.about-content strong {
				color: var(--primary);
				font-weight: 600;
			}
			.about-footer {
				margin-top: 28px;
			}
			.social-icons {
				display: flex;
				gap: 18px;
				flex-wrap: wrap;
				font-size: 14px;
			}
			.social-icons a {
				color: var(--secondary);
				text-decoration: underline;
				text-underline-offset: 0.25rem;
			}
			.social-icons a:hover {
				color: var(--primary);
			}

			@media (max-width: 800px) {
				.about-header h1 { font-size: 28px; }
			}
		</style>
	</body>
</html>
